    "A little further on was a brazier, a praying stool in crimson velvet, relieved with small bosses of gold.--*Paris*",
    "Finally, at the extreme end of the room, a simple bed of scarlet and yellow damask, without either tinsel or lace; having only an ordinary fringe.--*Paris*",
    "This bed, famous for having borne the sleep or the sleeplessness of Louis XI., was still to be seen two hundred years ago, at the house of a councillor of state, where it was seen by old Madame Pilou, celebrated in _Cyrus_ under the name \"Arricidie\" and of \"la Morale Vivante\".--*Paris*",
    "Such was the chamber which was called \"the retreat where Monsieur Louis de France says his prayers.\"--*Paris*",
    "At the moment when we have introduced the reader into it, this retreat was very dark.--*Paris*",
    "The curfew bell had sounded an hour before; night was come, and there was only one flickering wax candle set on the table to light five persons variously grouped in the chamber.--*Paris*",
